### 7.5 Writing JS Userland Programs

Every JS app in NephilimOS is a plain `.js` file executed inside MuJS by `SYS_JS_EXEC`. The runtime is stateless — each invocation gets a fresh JS state — but the filesystem persists between runs.

#### 7.5.1 File Layout

The conventional structure is an IIFE (immediately-invoked function expression) to keep all variables local and avoid polluting the global scope:

```javascript
(function() {
    var cwd  = typeof __cwd  !== 'undefined' ? __cwd  : '/';
    var args = typeof __args !== 'undefined' ? __args : [];

    /* ... your program ... */
})();
```

`__cwd` and `__args` are injected by the shell/exec preamble (see §7.4). Guarding with `typeof` lets the script run safely even if executed directly via `SYS_JS_EXEC` without a preamble.

#### 7.5.2 Path Resolution

Relative paths must be resolved against `__cwd` manually — MuJS has no concept of a working directory:

```javascript
function resolvePath(p) {
    if (p.charAt(0) === '/') return p;
    var base = (typeof __cwd !== 'undefined') ? __cwd : '/';
    if (base.charAt(base.length - 1) !== '/') base = base + '/';
    return base + p;
}
```

Use this before every `fsOpen` / `fsStat` / `fsMkdir` call when the path might be relative.

#### 7.5.3 Reading Files

```javascript
var fd = fsOpen(resolvePath(args[0]), "r");
if (fd < 0) { println("error: cannot open " + args[0]); return; }

var chunk;
while ((chunk = fsRead(fd, 4096)) !== null) {
    print(chunk);
}
fsClose(fd);
```

`fsRead` returns a string of up to `len` bytes, or `null` at EOF. Read in chunks — there is no guarantee the whole file arrives in one call.

#### 7.5.4 Writing Files

```javascript
var fd = fsOpen(resolvePath(args[0]), "w");   /* truncate/create */
if (fd < 0) { println("error: cannot write"); return; }
fsWrite(fd, "hello, world\n");
fsClose(fd);
```

Open modes:

| Mode | Behaviour |
|------|-----------|
| `"r"` | Read-only; file must exist |
| `"w"` | Write; create if absent, truncate if present |
| `"a"` | Append; create if absent, seek to end before every write |
| `"r+"` | Read+write; file must exist; no truncation |

#### 7.5.5 Stat and Directory Listing

```javascript
var info = fsStat(resolvePath(args[0]));
if (!info) { println("not found"); return; }
println("size:  " + info.size);
println("inode: " + info.ino);
println("mode:  " + info.mode.toString(8));
println("mtime: " + info.mtime);     /* seconds since epoch */
```

Directory listing:

```javascript
var fd = fsOpen(resolvePath(path), "r");
if (fd < 0) { println("cannot open dir"); return; }
var i = 0, entry;
while ((entry = fsReaddir(fd, i)) !== null) {
    println(entry.name);
    i++;
}
fsClose(fd);
```

#### 7.5.6 Interactive Programs

Use `readline()` for line input and `getChar()` / `getKeyNonBlock()` for keypress-level control:

```javascript
/* Simple prompt loop */
for (;;) {
    print("input> ");
    var line = readline();
    if (line === null || line === "quit") break;
    println("you typed: " + line);
}
```

For real-time apps (games, editors) poll `getKeyNonBlock()` and pace with `getTicks()` or `getGameTick()`:

```javascript
var last = getGameTick();
for (;;) {
    var k = getKeyNonBlock();
    if (k === 113 /* 'q' */) break;

    var now = getGameTick();
    if (now !== last) {
        last = now;
        /* update game state at ~10 Hz */
    }
}
```

#### 7.5.7 Terminal Control

```javascript
clearScreen();
hideCursor();

/* Draw a box at character cell (10, 5) */
vgaPoke(10, 5, 43 /* '+' */, 0x0F);   /* attr = white on black */
setCursor(0, 24);
showCursor();
```

`vgaPoke(col, row, charCode, attr)` writes one cell. `attr` is a VGA attribute byte: low nibble = foreground colour (0–15), high nibble = background colour (0–7). On the GOP path the driver translates these to 24-bit RGB.

`setColor(fg, bg)` sets the colour for subsequent `print` / `println` calls.

`printAt(col, row, str)` prints a string starting at the given cell position without moving the global cursor.

#### 7.5.8 Audio

```javascript
/* 440 Hz A note for 200 ms */
var SYS_BEEP = 41;
/* No direct JS binding — invoke via exec from the shell, or call from C.
   JS apps cannot issue raw syscalls directly. */
```

There is currently no `beep()` JS binding. Audio access from JS userland is planned but not yet exposed.

#### 7.5.9 Complete Example: hello.js

```javascript
/* hello.js — write a greeting, print it back */
(function() {
    var cwd  = typeof __cwd  !== 'undefined' ? __cwd  : '/';
    var args = typeof __args !== 'undefined' ? __args : [];

    function resolvePath(p) {
        if (p.charAt(0) === '/') return p;
        if (cwd.charAt(cwd.length - 1) !== '/') cwd = cwd + '/';
        return cwd + p;
    }

    var name = args[0] || "world";
    var path = resolvePath("hello.txt");

    /* Write */
    var fd = fsOpen(path, "w");
    if (fd < 0) { println("cannot write " + path); return; }
    fsWrite(fd, "Hello, " + name + "!\n");
    fsClose(fd);

    /* Read back */
    fd = fsOpen(path, "r");
    if (fd < 0) { println("cannot read back"); return; }
    var chunk;
    while ((chunk = fsRead(fd, 256)) !== null) print(chunk);
    fsClose(fd);
})();
```

Save to disk (from the shell):

```
write /home/USER /* paste contents */
exec /home/USER NephilimOS
```

Or write it with quill, then run: `exec /home/USER NephilimOS`

#### 7.5.10 Running Scripts with exec

`exec` is a C shell built-in (not a JS app). It reads any `.js` file from the VFS, prepends the `__cwd`/`__args` preamble, and feeds the combined source to `SYS_JS_EXEC`.

```
exec <path> [arg1] [arg2] ...
```

- `<path>` may be absolute (`/home/USER or relative to cwd.
- Arguments after the path become `__args[0]`, `__args[1]`, …
- There is no shebang support — the file must be valid JS.
- Buffer limit: 16 KiB of source + 512 bytes of preamble headroom.

#### 7.5.11 Build Integration

To ship a script as a built-in app that the shell can invoke by name:

1. Place your `.js` file under `userland/` (e.g. `userland/coreutils/myapp.js`).
2. Add a `.js.h` rule to `Makefile` `JS_HEADERS`:
   ```makefile
   userland/coreutils/myapp.js.h: userland/coreutils/myapp.js
       $(PYTHON) tools/js2ch.py $< > $@
   ```
3. Add an embedded source in `userland/apps.c`:
   ```c
   static const char src_myapp[] =
   #include "coreutils/myapp.js.h"
   ;
   ```
4. Add an entry to the `apps[]` table in `apps.c`:
   ```c
   { "myapp", "myapp", src_myapp },
   ```
5. Add an embedded source and seed entry in `kernel/seed.c` following the same `seed_myapp` pattern.
6. The shell will now recognise `myapp` as a command, reading from `/bin/myapp` on disk with the embedded string as fallback.

